<Layout 
  title="Legal Precedents | Policy"
  description="Understand key legal precedents that have shaped the UK Armed Forces Compensation Scheme. Learn about important court decisions and their impact on compensation claims.">
  <div class="container my-5">
    <h1 class="display-4 mb-4">Legal Precedents in AFCS Cases</h1>
    <div class="row g-4">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <p class="lead">Legal precedents play a crucial role in shaping the interpretation and application of the Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS). This page highlights key court decisions that have influenced AFCS policies and claim outcomes.</p>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Landmark Cases</h2>
        <p>Several landmark cases have significantly impacted AFCS policies:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Smith v Ministry of Defence (2013) - Duty of care in combat situations</li>
          <li>R (on the application of Duncan) v Ministry of Defence (2009) - Time limits for claims</li>
          <li>JL v Secretary of State for Defence (2013) - Assessment of mental health conditions</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Interpretation of Service Causation</h2>
        <p>Cases that have shaped the understanding of service-related injuries:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>MOD v Wheeler (2016) - Defining 'caused by service'</li>
          <li>R (Goodwin) v Secretary of State for Defence (2018) - Pre-existing conditions aggravated by service</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Compensation Levels</h2>
        <p>Precedents affecting compensation amounts:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>R (Kuteh) v Secretary of State for Defence (2019) - Calculation of lump sum payments</li>
          <li>Jones v Secretary of State for Defence (2014) - Multiple injury awards</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Appeal Process Rulings</h2>
        <p>Cases that have influenced the appeal process:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>R (Jennings) v First-tier Tribunal (2020) - Scope of tribunal powers</li>
          <li>Secretary of State for Defence v AB (2010) - Burden of proof in appeals</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Impact on Current Claims</h2>
        <p>How these precedents affect current and future claims:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Broadened interpretation of service-related injuries in some areas</li>
          <li>Clarified time limits and exceptions for late claims</li>
          <li>Refined methods for calculating compensation in complex cases</li>
          <li>Enhanced consideration of mental health impacts</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="card bg-light mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">Related Information</h3>
            <ul class="list-unstyled">
              <li><a href="/policy/legislation" class="text-decoration-none">AFCS Legislation</a></li>
              <li><a href="/eligibility/appeal-process" class="text-decoration-none">Appeal Process</a></li>
              <li><a href="/support/legal-assistance" class="text-decoration-none">Legal Assistance</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">Legal Updates Newsletter</h3>
            <p>Stay informed about new legal precedents and their impact on AFCS claims.</p>
            <a href="/legal-updates-signup" class="btn btn-primary">Subscribe</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
